<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;dl&gt;</code> element (description list, formerly "definition list") contains groups of terms (<a href="/docs/elements/native/dt/"><code>&lt;dt&gt;</code></a>) and their descriptions (<a href="/docs/elements/native/dd/"><code>&lt;dd&gt;</code></a>). It represents an association list of name-value pairs.</p>
    <p>Unlike <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>, which use <code>&lt;li&gt;</code> elements, definition lists use the <code>&lt;dt&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;dd&gt;</code> pair structure.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Semantic Meaning</h2>
    <p>A description list conveys that:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Content consists of related name-value or term-description pairs</li>
      <li>Terms (<code>&lt;dt&gt;</code>) are keys or labels</li>
      <li>Descriptions (<code>&lt;dd&gt;</code>) are values or explanations</li>
      <li>Each term can have multiple descriptions, and vice versa</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Screen readers can announce the relationship between terms and descriptions, helping users understand the data structure.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Glossaries with terms and definitions</li>
      <li>Metadata displays (author, date, category)</li>
      <li>FAQ sections (question-answer pairs)</li>
      <li>Product specifications</li>
      <li>Contact information (label-value pairs)</li>
      <li>Any key-value or term-description data</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When Not to Use</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>For simple sequential items - use <a href="/docs/elements/native/ol/"><code>&lt;ol&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For unordered collections - use <a href="/docs/elements/native/ul/"><code>&lt;ul&gt;</code></a></li>
      <li>For tabular data with multiple columns - use <code>&lt;table&gt;</code></li>
      <li>For dialog/conversation markup - use other semantic elements</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

